      <field name="fulltext">THE SONG OF THE LOWER CLASSES. By ERNEST JONES. (Music, by John Lowry.âThis song can also be sung to the air of âThe Monks of Old.â) We plough and sewâwe're so very, very low That we delve in the dirty clay, Till we bless the plainâwith the golden grain, And the vale with the fragrant hay. Our place we knowâwe're so very low, 'Tis down at the landlord's feet: We're not too lowâthe bread to grow, But too low the bread to eat. Chorus: We're not too lowâthe bread to grow, But too low the bread to eat. Down, down we goâwe're so very very low, To the hell of the deep sunk mines, But we gather the proudest gems that glow When the crown of a despot shines. And whenever he lacksâupon our backs Fresh loads he deigns to lay: We're far too low to vote the tax, But not too low to pay. Chorus: We're far too low to vote the tax. But not too low to pay. We're lowâwe're lowâmere rabble, we know, But at our plastic power, The mould at the lordling's feet will grow Into palace and church and towerâ Then prostrate fallâin the rich man's hall, And cringe at the rich man's door: We're not too low to build the wall, But too low to tread the floor. Chorus: We're not too low to build the wall, But too low to tread the floor! We're lowâwe're lowâwe're very very low, Yet from our fingers glide The silken flowâand the robes that glow Round the limbs of the sons of pride. And what we getâand what we give, We know, and we know our share: We're not too low the cloth to weave, But too low the cloth to wear! Chorus: We're not too low the cloth to weave, But too low the cloth to wear! We're lowâwe're lowâwe're very very low, And yet when the trumpets ring, The thrust of a poor man's arm will go Thro' the heart of the proudest king. We're lowâwe're lowâour place we know, We're only the rank and file, We're not too lowâto kill the foe, But too low to touch the spoil. Chorus: We're not too low to kill the foe, But too low to touch the spoil. A SONG OF CROMWELL'S TIME. BY ERNEST JONES. (Air: âA Life on the Ocean Wave.â) A vote in the Laws they make! A home on the land I till! Where the hearts of the many break The cup of the few to fill. By the right of their laws I pine: But what are their laws to me? For I live by right divine, And that is the right to be free. A home in my native isle! A share in the wealth I heap! Where the rich in their revel smile, And the poor in their anger weep. The poorâthe poorâthe poor in their anger weep. The richâthe richâthe richâtheir revels keep. The strength that in numbers lies Each hour is making known: Pioneers of the truth, arise, And you shall not be left alone! We'll scatter their knavish rule, Like a prisoned storm set free, Till tyrant and tyrant's tool Have vanished from sea to sea. A home in my native isle! A share in the wealth I heap! Where the rich in their revel smile, And the poor in their anger weep. The poorâthe poorâthe poor in their anger weep. The richâthe richâthe richâtheir revels keep. At the word of the cruel few The clouds of the battle frown: But, long as the many are true, We'll say: let the storm come downâ And on as the masses sweep, Our cry shall meet them still: A share in the wealth we heap. A home on the land we till. A home in my native isle, A vote in the laws we keep, Then the rich, if they like, may smile, But the poor shall cease to weep. The poorâthe poorâthe poor shall cease to weep The richâthe richâthe richâtheir revels keep</field>
